<paragraph id="8BCCE301227CFFA9A9C61244FE96A8F6" blockId="5.[174,1233,575,1082]" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">
D i s t r i b u t i o n: uncertain, due to confusion with 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227CFFA9AA731244FF68A856" authority="(Meigen, 1822)" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227CFFA9AA731244FBC2A875" box="[854,1112,575,601]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">Epistrophe nitidicollis</emphasis>
(Meigen, 1822)
</taxonomicName>
, already known from 
<collectingCountry id="F364A391227CFFA9AB211224FDFEA856" box="[516,612,607,634]" name="Norway" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">Norway</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F364A391227CFFA9AB561224FD4AA856" box="[627,720,607,634]" name="Sweden" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">Sweden</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F364A391227CFFA9ABFA1224FCA7A856" box="[735,829,607,634]" name="Finland" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">Finland</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F364A391227CFFA9AA691224FC06A856" box="[844,924,607,634]" name="France" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">France</collectingCountry>
(Rhine valley in 
<collectingRegion id="49B72DE3227CFFA9AD561224FB5EA856" box="[1139,1220,607,634]" country="France" name="Alsace" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">Alsace</collectingRegion>
), 
<collectingCountry id="F364A391227CFFA9A98B1204FEA2A8B6" box="[174,312,639,666]" name="Switzerland" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
and Far East of 
<collectingCountry id="F364A391227CFFA9A8D31204FDD8A8B6" box="[502,578,639,666]" name="Russia" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">Russia</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="49B72DE3227CFFA9AB751204FCCFA8B6" box="[592,853,639,666]" country="Russia" name="Kamchatka" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">Kamchatka Peninsula</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="49B72DE3227CFFA9AA451204FBD0A8B6" box="[864,1098,639,666]" country="Russia" name="Khabarovsk" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">Khabarovsk Region</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="49B72DE3227CFFA9AD711204FE9EA896" country="Russia" name="Primorskiy" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">Primorsky Region</collectingRegion>
, Kuril Islands (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE29EF0227CFFA9A89012E4FDD3A896" author="Mutin, V. A." box="[437,585,671,698]" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" pagination="109 - 115" refId="ref4510" refString="Mutin, V. A. 1990. The new and little known hoverfly species (Diptera, Syrphidae) of the Soviet Far East and Siberia. The news of the Far East insect systematics. Vladivostok, 109 - 115 [In Russian]." type="book chapter" year="1990">Mutin, 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE29EF0227CFFA9AB7112E4FCEBA896" author="Mutin, V. A. &amp; Barkalov, A. V." box="[596,881,671,698]" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" pagination="342 - 500" refId="ref4594" refString="Mutin, V. A. &amp; Barkalov, A. V. 1999. Fam. Syrphidae - hoverflies. In: Lehr, P. A., ed. Key to the insects of Russian Far East. Vol. 6 (Diptera and Siphonaptera), pt. 1. Dalnauka Publishing House, Vladivostok, 342 - 500 [In Russian]." type="book chapter" year="1999">Mutin &amp; Barkalov, 1999</bibRefCitation>
; Speight, 2017); 
<collectingCountry id="F364A391227CFFA9AD1412E4FB0BA896" box="[1073,1169,671,698]" name="Ukraine" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">Ukraine</collectingCountry>
(first record).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCCE301227CFFAAA9C612A4FB0BAD1B" blockId="5.[174,1233,575,1082]" lastBlockId="6.[166,1225,1596,1847]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="247" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">
Diagnosis. 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227CFFA9A85A12A4FDA7A8D5" authorityName="Mutin" authorityYear="1990" box="[383,573,735,761]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olgae">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227CFFA9A85A12A4FDA7A8D5" box="[383,573,735,761]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">Epistrophe olgae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227CFFA9AA3312A4FB8BA8D5" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[790,1041,735,761]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227CFFA9AA3312A4FB8BA8D5" box="[790,1041,735,761]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">Epistrophe nitidicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(figs 21, 22, 26– 28), having the second basal cell of wing 20% or more bare of microtrichia, mesoscutum brightly shining, undusted, and tergite 5 partly black (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE29EF0227CFFA9AA051364FBD9A916" author="Speight, M. C. D. &amp; Sarthou, J. - P." box="[800,1091,799,826]" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" pagination="1 - 139" refId="ref5117" refString="Speight, M. C. D. &amp; Sarthou, J. - P. 2017. StN keys for the identification of the European species of various genera of Syrphidae 2017. Syrph the Net, the database of European Syrphidae (Diptera), 99, 1 - 139. Syrph the Net publications, Dublin." type="journal article" year="2017">Speight &amp; Sarthou, 2017</bibRefCitation>
). Both sexes can be separated from it by the orange-brown arista (figs 23–25) (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227CFFA9AAC2133BFB1AA975" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[999,1152,831,857]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227CFFA9AAC2133BFB1AA975" box="[999,1152,831,857]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">E. nitidicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, arista black or dark brown, as on figs 26–28) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE29EF0227CFFA9ABBD1324FC5CA956" author="Speight, M. C. D. &amp; Sarthou, J. - P." box="[664,966,863,890]" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" pagination="1 - 139" refId="ref5117" refString="Speight, M. C. D. &amp; Sarthou, J. - P. 2017. StN keys for the identification of the European species of various genera of Syrphidae 2017. Syrph the Net, the database of European Syrphidae (Diptera), 99, 1 - 139. Syrph the Net publications, Dublin." type="journal article" year="2017">Speight &amp; Sarthou, 2017</bibRefCitation>
), and the mesonotum shining with an olive or golden tint (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227CFFA9ABAC13FBFCB8A9B5" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[649,802,895,921]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227CFFA9ABAC13FBFCB8A9B5" box="[649,802,895,921]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">E. nitidicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the mesonotum shining black with a bluish tint) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE29EF0227CFFA9A87D13E4FDE4A996" author="Mutin, V. A. &amp; Barkalov, A. V." box="[344,638,927,954]" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" pagination="342 - 500" refId="ref4594" refString="Mutin, V. A. &amp; Barkalov, A. V. 1999. Fam. Syrphidae - hoverflies. In: Lehr, P. A., ed. Key to the insects of Russian Far East. Vol. 6 (Diptera and Siphonaptera), pt. 1. Dalnauka Publishing House, Vladivostok, 342 - 500 [In Russian]." type="book chapter" year="1999">Mutin &amp; Barkalov, 1999</bibRefCitation>
). Male can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227CFFA9AD3613DBFB36A995" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[1043,1196,927,953]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227CFFA9AD3613DBFB36A995" box="[1043,1196,927,953]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">E. nitidicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the frons with a grey or golden (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE29EF0227CFFA9AB1713C4FD5DA9F6" author="Mutin, V. A." box="[562,711,959,986]" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" pagination="109 - 115" refId="ref4510" refString="Mutin, V. A. 1990. The new and little known hoverfly species (Diptera, Syrphidae) of the Soviet Far East and Siberia. The news of the Far East insect systematics. Vladivostok, 109 - 115 [In Russian]." type="book chapter" year="1990">Mutin, 1990</bibRefCitation>
) or faint yellow-gray dust (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227CFFA9AD1413BBFB53A9F5" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[1073,1225,959,985]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227CFFA9AD1413BBFB53A9F5" box="[1073,1225,959,985]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">E. nitidicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the frons with a distinct grey dust) (Bartsh et al., 2009; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE29EF0227CFFA9AA6913A4FBEFA9D6" author="Speight, M. C. D. &amp; Sarthou, J. - P." box="[844,1141,991,1018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" pagination="1 - 139" refId="ref5117" refString="Speight, M. C. D. &amp; Sarthou, J. - P. 2017. StN keys for the identification of the European species of various genera of Syrphidae 2017. Syrph the Net, the database of European Syrphidae (Diptera), 99, 1 - 139. Syrph the Net publications, Dublin." type="journal article" year="2017">Speight &amp; Sarthou, 2017</bibRefCitation>
); in the Ukrainian specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227CFFA9A8F4147BFDAAAE35" authorityName="Mutin" authorityYear="1990" box="[465,560,1023,1049]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olgae">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227CFFA9A8F4147BFDAAAE35" box="[465,560,1023,1049]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">E. olgae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the frons with distinct golden dust (fig. 23), while in 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227CFFA9A98B145BFEDEAE15" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[174,324,1055,1081]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227CFFA9A98B145BFEDEAE15" box="[174,324,1055,1081]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">E. nitidicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the frons with a yellowish-gray dust (fig. 26). Female differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227CFFA9AD1F145BFB4AAE15" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[1082,1232,1055,1081]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227CFFA9AD1F145BFB4AAE15" box="[1082,1232,1055,1081]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="246">E. nitidicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the frons almost entirely dusted brownish-grey (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227FFFAAAA081646FC5CAC7A" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[813,966,1596,1622]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227FFFAAAA081646FC5CAC7A" box="[813,966,1596,1622]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="247">E. nitidicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the frons with a pair of brownish-grey dust spots, though these dust spots may be joined in the mid-line), the vertex pollinose with a brownish-grey dust, lateral to the ocellar triangle (fig. 25) (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227FFFAAA98316E6FEA6AC9A" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[166,316,1692,1718]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227FFFAAA98316E6FEA6AC9A" box="[166,316,1692,1718]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="247">E. nitidicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the vertex shining black, undusted, lateral to the ocellar triangle, as on fig. 28) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE29EF0227FFFAAA98B16C7FE4FACFB" author="Speight, M. C. D. &amp; Sarthou, J. - P." box="[174,469,1724,1751]" pageId="6" pageNumber="247" pagination="1 - 139" refId="ref5117" refString="Speight, M. C. D. &amp; Sarthou, J. - P. 2017. StN keys for the identification of the European species of various genera of Syrphidae 2017. Syrph the Net, the database of European Syrphidae (Diptera), 99, 1 - 139. Syrph the Net publications, Dublin." type="journal article" year="2017">Speight &amp; Sarthou, 2017</bibRefCitation>
). In the Ukrainian specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227FFFAAAA6B16C6FC33ACFA" authorityName="Mutin" authorityYear="1990" box="[846,937,1724,1750]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olgae">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227FFFAAAA6B16C6FC33ACFA" box="[846,937,1724,1750]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="247">E. olgae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the frons with a pair of almost separated (figs 24, 25), yellowish-grey dust spots (but the frons between these spots faintly pollinose, not shining), whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227FFFAAABB41686FCBDAD3A" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[657,807,1788,1814]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227FFFAAABB41686FCBDAD3A" box="[657,807,1788,1814]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="247">E. nitidicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, these yellowish-grey dust spots are distinctly separated, and the frons between this pollinose spots is shining (figs 27, 28).
</paragraph>
