<paragraph id="8BCCE301227EFFABA9C210D5FE28AB65" blockId="7.[178,1236,174,329]" pageId="7" pageNumber="248">
N o t e. It is noteworthy that the descriptions (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE29EF0227EFFABABD610D5FC1CAAE5" author="Mutin, V. A." box="[755,902,174,201]" pageId="7" pageNumber="248" pagination="109 - 115" refId="ref4510" refString="Mutin, V. A. 1990. The new and little known hoverfly species (Diptera, Syrphidae) of the Soviet Far East and Siberia. The news of the Far East insect systematics. Vladivostok, 109 - 115 [In Russian]." type="book chapter" year="1990">Mutin, 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE29EF0227EFFABAAB510D5FB32AAE5" author="Mutin, V. A. &amp; Barkalov, A. V." box="[912,1192,174,201]" pageId="7" pageNumber="248" pagination="342 - 500" refId="ref4594" refString="Mutin, V. A. &amp; Barkalov, A. V. 1999. Fam. Syrphidae - hoverflies. In: Lehr, P. A., ed. Key to the insects of Russian Far East. Vol. 6 (Diptera and Siphonaptera), pt. 1. Dalnauka Publishing House, Vladivostok, 342 - 500 [In Russian]." type="book chapter" year="1999">Mutin &amp; Barkalov, 1999</bibRefCitation>
) do not mention that 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227EFFABA85A10B4FE42AAC4" authorityName="Mutin" authorityYear="1990" box="[383,472,206,232]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olgae">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227EFFABA85A10B4FE42AAC4" box="[383,472,206,232]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="248">E. olgae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an orange-brown arista. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE29EF0227EFFABAA0F10B5FC5DAAC5" author="Mutin, V. A." box="[810,967,206,233]" pageId="7" pageNumber="248" pagination="109 - 115" refId="ref4510" refString="Mutin, V. A. 1990. The new and little known hoverfly species (Diptera, Syrphidae) of the Soviet Far East and Siberia. The news of the Far East insect systematics. Vladivostok, 109 - 115 [In Russian]." type="book chapter" year="1990">Mutin (1990)</bibRefCitation>
describes it as a brown arista, but it has not been included among distinctions of 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227EFFABAA7F1094FC2EAB24" authorityName="Mutin" authorityYear="1990" box="[858,948,238,264]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olgae">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227EFFABAA7F1094FC2EAB24" box="[858,948,238,264]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="248">E. olgae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="4C739882227EFFABAAD81094FB0EAB24" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[1021,1172,238,264]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Epistrophe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">
<emphasis id="B9073F13227EFFABAAD81094FB0EAB24" box="[1021,1172,238,264]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="248">E. nitidicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This remarkable character (among others) clearly differentiates these two species among the Ukrainian specimens.
</paragraph>
